Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

Here, we'll be analyzing a dataset on hospital appointment records, and we'll be interested in finding trends that distinguish between patients who show up for the appointments they have scheduled and the ones who do not.

This dataset wasderived as a result ofdata collectedfrom a 100,000Brazilian medical appointments made. The datasetfocuses on whether or not patients turn up to theirscheduled doctor visits. Every recordcontains some piecesof information about the patient. Each record consists of data from 14 columns: Patient ID,Appointment ID,Gender, Scheduled Day, Neighborhood,Appointment Day, Scholarship,Age,Hyper-tension,Diabetes,Alcoholism,Handicap,SMS_received, andNo-show.

Scheduled Day indicates when the patient has scheduled their appointment.

Neighbourhood refers to the hospital's location.

Scholarship denotes whether or not the patient is registered in the Bolsa Famlia, a Brazilian welfare programme.

No-showreads 'No' if the patient turned up for their appointment, and 'Yes' if they did not.

Main Research Question:¶

What criteria should we be aware of in order to forecast whether or not a patient will make an appearance for their planned appointment?¶

In order to answer this question we have to look into the effect of each independent variable on the action of missing appointment, these independent variables that we'll look into are:

  1. Patient Specific Charachteristics ('patient_id')
  2. Age ('age')
  3. Alcoholism ('alcoholism')
  4. Diabetes ('diabetes')
  5. Handicap ('handicap')
  6. Hypertension ('hyper_tension')
  7. Scholarship ('scholarship')
  8. Whether a Reminding Text Message was Sent ('sms_received')
  9. Time Separating the Date of Scheduling the Appointment and the Appointment Date

This is actually quite interesting. The graphs are intensely dissimilar which shows that there is a correlation between age and showing up! From the graphs shown above, it shows that patients who are parents are keen on taking their infants to their doctor appointments which explains the surge around age 0 in figure 1 and drop around the same age in figure 2. Also, it seems like patients of old age are committed to go to their doctors appointment, which explains the surge in Figure 1. In figure 2, the graph is terminated at age 100 because the dataset doesn't seem to include any patient with age > 100 that did not show up to their doctor appointments, which proves the theory mentioned above.

#first, we split the dataset by the 'turned_up' mask which gives us a separate dataframe that only consists of-
#- the patients who showed up.
#Second, we split them into groups charachterized by their gender, then get the counts for each group.
#Finally, we divide those counts with the total number of samples (of those who showed up and those who didn't),
#to get a normalized ratio!

gender_ratio_turnup = df[turned_up].groupby(['gender']).size()/df.groupby(['gender']).size()
index = ['Female', 'Male']
height = gender_ratio_turnup
plt.bar(index, height)
plt.ylabel('Percentage of Showing Up')
plt.title('Percentage of Patients Showing Up in Reference to their Gender')
